.TH SIMPLE_SHELL 1 "November 2025" "Simple Shell 1.0" "User Commands"

.SH NAME
hsh \- simple UNIX command-line interpreter

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B ./hsh
.br
.B command
| 
.B ./hsh

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B hsh
is a simple UNIX command-line interpreter written in C as the final project
of the first trimester at Holberton School. It replicates the core behavior
of
.BR /bin/sh ,
providing a prompt, reading user input, parsing commands and arguments,
locating executables via the
.B PATH
environment variable, and executing them in a child process via
.BR fork (2)
and
.BR execve (2).

The shell can operate in two modes:

.TP
.B Interactive mode
When standard input is connected to a terminal, the shell displays the prompt
.B "$ "
and waits for the user to enter a command.

.TP
.B Non-interactive mode
When standard input is a pipe or a file, the shell reads and executes
commands without displaying a prompt.

.SH INVOCATION
After compilation, run the shell with:

.RS
.B ./hsh
.RE

To pipe commands into the shell:

.RS
.B echo "ls -l" | ./hsh
.RE

.SH BUILT-IN COMMANDS
The following commands are handled internally by
.B hsh
and are not forked into separate processes:

.TP
.B exit
Exit the shell. The shell returns the exit status of the last executed command.

.TP
.B env
Print the current environment, one variable per line in the form
.IR NAME=VALUE .

.SH COMMAND EXECUTION
When a command is entered that is not a built-in:
.IP \(bu 2
If the command contains a
.B /
character, it is treated as an absolute or relative path and executed directly.
.IP \(bu 2
Otherwise, the shell searches each directory listed in the
.B PATH
environment variable for an executable file matching the command name.
.IP \(bu 2
If the command is found, it is executed in a child process via
.BR execve (2).
The parent shell waits for the child to finish and stores its exit status.
.IP \(bu 2
If the command is not found, an error message is printed to standard error
and the shell returns exit code
.BR 127 .

.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B PATH
A colon-separated list of directories searched to locate executable commands.

.SH EXIT STATUS
.B hsh
returns the exit status of the last executed command. Special values:
.IP \(bu 2
.B 0
\(en command completed successfully.
.IP \(bu 2
.B 127
\(en command not found.
.IP \(bu 2
Any other value reflects the exit status of the last executed program.

.SH ERROR MESSAGES
When a command is not found, the shell prints an error in the following format:

.RS
.IR shell_name :\ 1 :\ command :\ not\ found
.RE

For example:

.RS
.B ./hsh: 1: wrongcommand: not found
.RE

.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Run a simple command:
.B $ ls
.br
AUTHORS.txt  main.c  README.md  shell.h

.TP
Run a command with arguments:
.B $ ls -la /tmp

.TP
Use the built-in
.BR env :
.br
.B $ env
.br
PATH=/usr/local/bin:/usr/bin
.br
HOME=/home/user

.TP
Exit the shell:
.B $ exit

.SH SIGNALS
Sending
.B EOF
(Ctrl+D) to the shell in interactive mode causes it to exit cleanly and
print a newline.

